<!--
========================================================================
FILE: App.view.xml — The Root View of the ShopEasy Application
NAMESPACE: com.shopeasy.app.view
========================================================================

[BEGINNER] WHAT IS AN XML VIEW?
An XML view is a declarative way to define your user interface in SAP UI5.
Instead of writing JavaScript code to create buttons, lists, and pages,
you describe them in XML — much like writing HTML.

Think of it like this:
  HTML:  <div class="container"><button>Click</button></div>
  UI5:   <Page><Button text="Click" /></Page>

The XML is parsed by the UI5 runtime and converted into JavaScript
control objects internally. You NEVER manipulate the XML at runtime —
it's a one-time blueprint.

[BEGINNER] WHY XML AND NOT JAVASCRIPT?
UI5 supports 4 view types: XML, JavaScript, JSON, and HTML.
XML is the RECOMMENDED and STANDARD choice because:
  1. It separates structure (XML view) from logic (JS controller)
  2. UI5 tooling (code completion, linting) works best with XML
  3. SAP Fiori guidelines mandate XML views
  4. XML views enable declarative data binding (we'll see examples below)
  5. Easier to read and review in code reviews

[BEGINNER] HOW DOES THIS VIEW CONNECT TO A CONTROLLER?
The controllerName attribute on the <mvc:View> tag tells UI5 which
JavaScript controller file to pair with this view. UI5 loads the
controller, creates an instance, and calls its lifecycle methods
(onInit, onBeforeRendering, onAfterRendering, onExit).

  controllerName="com.shopeasy.app.controller.App"
    → Resolves to: webapp/controller/App.controller.js

The view and controller communicate through:
  - this.getView()   — Controller accesses its view
  - this.getController() — View accesses its controller (rarely needed in XML)

[INTERMEDIATE] HOW DOES THIS VIEW GET LOADED?
This view is declared as the "rootView" in manifest.json:
  "rootView": {
    "viewName": "com.shopeasy.app.view.App",
    "type": "XML",
    "id": "app",
    "async": true
  }
When the Component initializes, it loads this root view first. All other
views are then rendered INSIDE this view via the Router.

[ADVANCED] VIEW LIFECYCLE:
  1. UI5 parses this XML file
  2. For each XML element, UI5 creates the corresponding JS control
  3. Data bindings are resolved and connected to models
  4. The controller's onInit() is called
  5. onBeforeRendering() is called
  6. Controls render themselves into the DOM
  7. onAfterRendering() is called
  8. When navigating away: onExit() is called for cleanup

Learn more: docs/02-views-and-controllers.md
========================================================================
-->

<!--
[BEGINNER] THE <mvc:View> ROOT ELEMENT
Every XML view MUST have <mvc:View> as its root element. This tells UI5
"this XML file is a View" and provides the container for all controls.

Attributes explained:
  - controllerName:  The fully-qualified name of the paired controller
  - xmlns:           The DEFAULT XML namespace — controls from this library
                     don't need a prefix (e.g., <App>, <Page>, <Button>)
  - xmlns:mvc:       The namespace for the View control itself
  - xmlns:core:      Namespace for core controls (e.g., core:Fragment)

[BEGINNER] UNDERSTANDING XML NAMESPACES (xmlns)
Namespaces prevent name collisions. UI5 has MANY libraries, and different
libraries might have controls with the same name. Namespaces solve this:

  xmlns="sap.m"           → Default. <Button> means sap.m.Button
  xmlns:core="sap.ui.core" → <core:Icon> means sap.ui.core.Icon
  xmlns:l="sap.ui.layout" → <l:Grid> means sap.ui.layout.Grid

The default namespace (xmlns without a prefix) is the one you use MOST.
Since sap.m contains the majority of controls you'll use (Button, Page,
List, Input, etc.), it's almost always the default.

[BEST PRACTICE] Always use these standard prefix conventions:
  xmlns="sap.m"                    (default — no prefix needed)
  xmlns:mvc="sap.ui.core.mvc"     (always "mvc" for the View)
  xmlns:core="sap.ui.core"        (always "core" for core controls)
  xmlns:l="sap.ui.layout"         (always "l" for layout controls)
  xmlns:f="sap.f"                 (always "f" for Fiori controls)
  xmlns:unified="sap.ui.unified"  (always "unified" for unified controls)

Using consistent prefixes across your project makes the codebase
predictable and easier for your team to navigate.

[INTERMEDIATE] NAMESPACE RESOLUTION AT RUNTIME
When UI5 parses <Button text="Hello" />, it:
  1. Sees no prefix → uses the default namespace "sap.m"
  2. Resolves to the class sap.m.Button
  3. Loads the module "sap/m/Button" (if not already loaded)
  4. Creates: new sap.m.Button({ text: "Hello" })

When it sees <core:Icon src="sap-icon://home" />, it:
  1. Sees prefix "core" → uses namespace "sap.ui.core"
  2. Resolves to sap.ui.core.Icon
  3. Creates: new sap.ui.core.Icon({ src: "sap-icon://home" })
-->
<mvc:View
    controllerName="com.shopeasy.app.controller.App"
    xmlns="sap.m"
    xmlns:mvc="sap.ui.core.mvc"
    xmlns:core="sap.ui.core"
>
    <!--
    [BEGINNER] THE <App> CONTROL — Navigation Container
    ====================================================
    sap.m.App is the ROOT CONTROL for mobile-style (responsive) applications.
    It serves as a NavContainer — a container that holds pages and handles
    animated transitions between them when navigating.

    Think of App like a deck of cards:
      - Only ONE card (page) is visible at a time
      - When you navigate, a new card slides in from the right
      - When you go back, the previous card slides in from the left

    id="app"
      This ID is CRITICAL because it's referenced in the routing config
      (manifest.json → sap.ui5.routing.config.controlId: "app").
      The Router uses this ID to find the container where it should
      render target views.

    [INTERMEDIATE] HOW ROUTING USES THIS APP CONTROL
    The manifest.json routing config specifies:
      controlId: "app"              → Find the control with id="app"
      controlAggregation: "pages"   → Put views into its "pages" aggregation

    When a route matches (e.g., user navigates to #/cart):
      1. Router finds this <App id="app"> control
      2. Creates/retrieves the Cart view
      3. Adds it to the "pages" aggregation
      4. Calls app.to(cartPage) to animate the transition

    [ADVANCED] sap.m.App vs sap.m.NavContainer vs sap.m.SplitApp
      - sap.m.App: Extends NavContainer, adds viewport meta tag handling
        and platform-specific styling. Use this as your outermost container.
      - sap.m.NavContainer: Pure navigation container without App-specific
        features. Use inside App for nested navigation.
      - sap.m.SplitApp: Two-column layout (master/detail) for tablet/desktop.
        Use for apps with a persistent side panel (like email clients).

    [BEST PRACTICE] BUSY INDICATOR SUPPORT
    The busy and busyIndicatorDelay attributes enable a loading overlay
    on the entire app. This is useful during initial data loading:
      busy="{appView>/busy}"                → Shows spinner when true
      busyIndicatorDelay="{appView>/delay}" → Delay before showing (ms)

    Why a delay? To avoid flickering for fast operations. If data loads
    in 100ms, you don't want a spinner to flash for 100ms — it looks
    broken. A delay of 300-500ms means the spinner only shows for
    operations that take noticeably long.
    -->
    <App id="app">
        <!--
        [INTERMEDIATE] WHY IS THE <App> CONTROL EMPTY?
        ===============================================
        You might expect to see <pages> with views listed here, but the
        App control starts EMPTY. The Router dynamically adds pages at
        runtime based on the URL hash:

          URL: #/           → Router adds Home.view.xml to pages
          URL: #/cart       → Router adds Cart.view.xml to pages
          URL: #/product/1  → Router adds ProductDetail.view.xml to pages

        This is the power of routing — views are loaded ON DEMAND, not
        all at once. This improves initial load time because the app
        only loads the view the user actually needs.

        [ADVANCED] LAZY LOADING VIEWS
        By default, views are created when their route is first matched
        and then cached. On subsequent navigations to the same route,
        the cached view instance is reused (no re-creation). This is
        why onInit() runs only ONCE per view, but the route's
        patternMatched event fires on EVERY navigation.
        -->
    </App>

</mvc:View>
